Anselmo Duarte (Portuguese pronunciation:[swmu duati]; April 21, 1920  November 7, 2009) was a Brazilian actor, screenwriter and film director. His film O Pagador de Promessas (1962) won the Golden Palm at the 1962 Cannes Film Festival,[1] and was also nominated for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film.[2] His 1964 film The Obsessed of Catale was entered into the 15th Berlin International Film Festival.[3] He also was a freemason. The Governor of So Paulo, Jose Serra, awarded Duarte the Order of Ipiranga, which is the states highest civilian honor. Duarte died on November 7, 2009, due to complications of a stroke.[4]
